 Java -- tCHAPTER 13. Colonialism and the Built Space of Cinema -- tSection II: Postcolonial Looking -- tIntroduction -- tPART 5: SUBALTERN SEEING: AN OVERLAP OF COMPLEXITIES -- tCHAPTER 14. Speaking Back to Orientalist Discourse -- tCHAPTER 15. Maps, Mother/Goddesses, and Martyrdom in Modern India -- tCHAPTER 16. Notes from the Surface of the Image: Photography, Postcolonialism, and Vernacular Modernism -- tCHAPTER 17. "I Am Rendered Speechless by Your Idea of Beauty": The Picturesque in History and Art in the Postcolony -- tCHAPTER 18. Fanon, Algeria, and the Cinema: The Politics of Identification -- tPART 6: REGARDING AND RECONSTITUTING EUROPE -- tCHAPTER 19. Creole Europe: The Reflection of a Reflection -- tCHAPTER 20. Picasso, Africa, and the Schemata of Difference -- tCHAPTER 21. Double Dutch and the Culture Game -- tConclusion: A Parting Glance: Empire and Visuality -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmpires of Vision brings together pieces by some of the most influential scholars working at the intersection of visual culture studies and the history of European imperialism. The essays and excerpts focus on the paintings, maps, geographical surveys, postcards, photographs, and other media that comprise the visual milieu of colonization, struggles for decolonization, and the lingering effects of empire. Taken together, they demonstrate that an appreciation of the role of visual experience is necessary for understanding the functioning of hegemonic imperial power and the ways that the colonized subjects spoke, and looked, back at their imperial rulers. Empires of Vision also makes a vital point about the complexity of image culture in the modern world: We must comprehend how regimes of visuality emerged globally, not only in the metropole but also in relation to the putative margins of a world that increasingly came to question the very distinction between center and periphery.Contributors. Jordanna Bailkin, Roger Benjamin, Daniela Bleichmar, Zeynep Çelik, David Ciarlo, Natasha Eaton, Simon Gikandi, Serge Gruzinski, James L. Hevia, Martin Jay, Brian Larkin, Olu Oguibe, Ricardo Padrón, Christopher Pinney, Sumathi Ramaswamy, Benjamin Schmidt, Terry Smith, Robert Stam, Eric A. Stein, Nicholas Thomas, Krista A. Thompson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh1 aSchmidt, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarkin, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinney, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBleichmar, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiarlo, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStein, Eric A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHevia, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJay, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBailkin, Jordanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Krista A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJay, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEaton, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOguibe, Olu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamaswamy, Sumathi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPadrón, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStam, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo